WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.440
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger. In&nbsp;
this video, we're going to look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:17.040
the arithmetic of natural numbers&nbsp;
from a somewhat new point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:23.850
with this data structure orientation relying&nbsp;
particularly on the notion of an M-set or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:31.350
multiset. An interesting feature of this&nbsp;
is that we are really looking at using the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:40.650
idea of nothing in a novel fashion here, so&nbsp;
there's an opportunity for really rethinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.650 --> 00:00:46.590
this fundamental building block or pillar of&nbsp;
mathematics. Arithmetic with natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:51.090
after all, is absolutely fundamental in&nbsp;
setting up so much of modern mathematics.

00:00:51.090 --> 00:01:00.750
So, the interesting kind of idea or dichotomy&nbsp;
that I introduced a few videos back is that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.750 --> 00:01:08.850
can start off, when we're building up mathematics&nbsp;
right at level zero, by thinking about nothing and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.850 --> 00:01:18.090
something—these two fundamental orientations:&nbsp;
nothing being a blank page, an empty space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:25.020
and something being represented by some kind&nbsp;
of mark, maybe a unit, something relatively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:32.910
simple that represents to us something. Okay, and&nbsp;
this gives us the beginnings of the new framework&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:38.730
for arithmetic, where we start by defining&nbsp;
a natural number to be an M-set of marks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.730 --> 00:01:44.790
the simplest marks, such as, for example, this&nbsp;
thing here. So, we have an M-set—it means we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:55.080
have square brackets, and inside we have some&nbsp;
marks, and that's what a natural number is. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.080 --> 00:02:00.240
it's very simplistic; it's really capturing&nbsp;
the same kind of orientation that we had in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:05.520
our very first video, but it's a little bit more&nbsp;
sophisticated because now we're putting things in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:14.340
the multiset framework. And we can now be more&nbsp;
precise and say that "nat" represents the type&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.340 --> 00:02:20.760
of natural numbers represented this way. So, in&nbsp;
this formulation of things, you have a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:25.650
number precisely when you've gone through the&nbsp;
trouble of writing out an expression like this.

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:32.190
An important distinction between what we're doing&nbsp;
now and the way we started the series is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.190 --> 00:02:39.420
now the empty multiset is going to be included&nbsp;
as a possible natural number because if we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:45.570
thinking about natural numbers as being M-sets of&nbsp;
marks, then it's possible to have an empty M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:53.760
and that empty M-set we're going to call zero.&nbsp;
So, that's our distinguished zero object in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:59.010
our world of natural numbers now. So, that's a&nbsp;
distinction between the way we started the series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:03.840
where zero was not included—historically,&nbsp;
zero is not really a natural number—but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:08.730
with this sort of more modern point of view,&nbsp;
we are including zero in the natural numbers.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:12.900
So, to summarize, the fundamental&nbsp;
ingredients that we really have here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:18.540
okay, in this setting up of natural numbers&nbsp;
are the two concepts of nothing and something,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:26.520
represented by emptiness—just nothing on the&nbsp;
page—and represented by this mark or this unit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:31.170
something which doesn't have to be a&nbsp;
straight line. It could be something else;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:36.210
it could be a little circle or dot, something&nbsp;
else. But it should be uniform, so they should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:43.080
all look the same, and it should be something&nbsp;
simple, something kind of fundamental and very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:48.600
easy to write down. And the other thing that we&nbsp;
need, of course, are brackets—the brackets that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:58.680
we're using to denote multisets that contain our&nbsp;
bunches of marks so that we know where they end,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:03.600
so they're bounded, and we have&nbsp;
control over where they actually are.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:08.700
And so, we have these things called natural&nbsp;
numbers, and here are some examples. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:11.730
there's a natural number, there's a&nbsp;
natural number, there's one, there's one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:15.090
there's another one, there's another one,&nbsp;
there's another one, then there's the empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.090 --> 00:04:21.930
set natural number—they're all natural numbers.&nbsp;
Now, some of them might be the same—for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:26.800
this one here looks a lot like this&nbsp;
one, and these are the same—but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:35.260
that's fine. Notice that there's not intrinsically&nbsp;
necessarily an order to them at this point—maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:41.080
a bit of a subtle issue, but we're just saying&nbsp;
what a natural number is. We have not yet gone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.080 --> 00:04:47.170
to the trouble of organizing them all&nbsp;
in some kind of list or pattern. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:54.070
we've just identified what it means for an&nbsp;
expression to be a natural number of type "nat."

00:04:54.070 --> 00:05:03.910
And let us compare this view to the 20th-century&nbsp;
view of natural numbers, which was reliant on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:12.670
prior set theory and posited that natural numbers&nbsp;
were things that were cooked up from sets of sets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:19.330
subsets and such, basically starting with the&nbsp;
empty set. So, for example, the number four was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:27.370
the set {0, 1, 2, 3}, where 0 was the empty set,&nbsp;
one was the set involving the empty set, two was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:38.590
the set consisting of 0 as well as one, and three&nbsp;
is the set, well, consisting of 0, 1, and 2. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.590 --> 00:05:49.240
in the 20th century, the view was that the number&nbsp;
4 officially is this thing. Now, our view, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:56.140
is a 21st-century point of view—we're moving ahead&nbsp;
here—is that the number 4 is represented by this:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.140 --> 00:06:03.790
it's a multiset which has these marks in&nbsp;
it. I want you to compare these two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.790 --> 00:06:11.320
all right, and objectively, scientifically,&nbsp;
rationally tell me which one is better,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:21.940
which one corresponds naturally to the way&nbsp;
people think about natural numbers. Which of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:27.250
these views do you think supports a more&nbsp;
sensible notion of operations, addition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:35.440
multiplication, and proofs, etc.? Okay, so it's&nbsp;
pretty clear what the answer is, of course.

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:39.400
And let's have a look at equality—the idea of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.070 --> 00:06:45.830
testifying when two expressions that we write down&nbsp;
are actually equal. It's a very important notion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:50.570
so we're going to have a look here. Here's&nbsp;
the definition: two natural numbers are equal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.570 --> 00:06:59.570
underline that, precisely when we can match up&nbsp;
their entries. What do I mean by that? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:05.570
here are two natural numbers—there's a natural&nbsp;
number, and there's a natural number—and the claim&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:11.240
here is that these are equal. And what does it&nbsp;
mean to be equal? Well, it means that we can match&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:19.070
up the entries from this one with the entries&nbsp;
from this one. So we'll match these and these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:24.350
these ones are going to get matched up, and these&nbsp;
are going to get matched up, and these are going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:31.280
to get matched up. You can also do that sort of&nbsp;
physically—these are matched up, and then these,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:36.680
and then these, and then these and the next.&nbsp;
Okay, so it's not really necessary to count them;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:42.980
we don't have to have a prior notion of counting&nbsp;
to do this, okay? We're just matching them up in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:49.970
the way that some primitive person might match&nbsp;
up, you know, five fingers with 5 X's on a piece&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:57.290
of bark—just match them up. Here we have a natural&nbsp;
number which is not equal to this natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.290 --> 00:08:01.550
and the reason is when we try to match&nbsp;
them up—say, match that one with that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:09.020
and match this one with this one, and match this&nbsp;
one with this one—well, then this one here does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.020 --> 00:08:13.640
not match up with anyone there, and so we can't&nbsp;
match them up, and so these two are not equal.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:25.700
So, this is meant to be simple, right? This is&nbsp;
meant to be a theory that a primary school student&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:32.570
can understand and appreciate and see, "Yeah,&nbsp;
this is corresponding with something reasonable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:39.920
something intuitive, something useful," right? So&nbsp;
now we come to a very important and interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.920 --> 00:08:48.170
development: what happens when we look at the&nbsp;
addition of natural numbers—the simplest and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:54.290
most fundamental operation in some sense?&nbsp;
Okay, so an interesting thing happens here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.290 --> 00:09:00.350
which again is probably going to go outside&nbsp;
your natural intuition and experience—we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:04.940
going to look at addition in a different way.&nbsp;
So it's usually considered that addition is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:10.220
a binary operation; that almost goes without&nbsp;
saying. When we're starting to do arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:16.970
in the usual framework, for example, we&nbsp;
say A equals B plus C—we have number B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.970 --> 00:09:23.780
we have a number C, we're adding them together to&nbsp;
get another number A. We start with two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:29.480
and we combine them, and we get another&nbsp;
number. But in the M-set framework,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:35.810
which is something that most modern students&nbsp;
of mathematics are not that familiar with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:43.970
in the M-set or multiset framework, we have&nbsp;
more flexibility, right? We can think a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:43.970 --> 00:09:51.290
bit bigger than we can, perhaps, with other&nbsp;
data structures. In particular, the multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:58.250
framework is not ordered naturally, and it's not&nbsp;
constrained by just having one of everything,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.250 --> 00:10:03.860
right? So we can deal with multiplicities with&nbsp;
M-sets, and we can deal with things not being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:12.020
ordered—that's the essential orientation. So that&nbsp;
affects us when it comes to defining addition.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:17.420
So it turns out that in the M-set framework,&nbsp;
having a binary operation is neither necessary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:26.420
nor desirable. What are we talking about here?&nbsp;
Well, to add natural numbers, what we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:32.420
do is we're going to form a new M-set containing&nbsp;
all of the entries of the M-sets that we have. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.420 --> 00:10:44.300
want to show you this physically, okay? So here&nbsp;
is a box, a blue box, and in this blue box, here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.300 --> 00:10:49.910
we see a couple of little boxes or containers.&nbsp;
So here's a container—it's got some coins in it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.910 --> 00:10:56.210
okay? There's another container, and then here's&nbsp;
another container—got some more coins in it. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.210 --> 00:11:03.380
here's a third container containing some&nbsp;
more coins, okay? So these are M-sets;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:08.860
it's a multiset of coins. There's some repetition,&nbsp;
and they're not ordered. This is another M-set of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:13.720
coins, and here's another M-set of coins. So&nbsp;
we have a couple of different M-sets of coins,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:17.770
and now I'm going to add them. I'm going to show&nbsp;
you how to do this physically—I'm probably going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:23.350
to drop this doing this, but okay. So I'm going&nbsp;
to take this one, and this one, and another one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.350 --> 00:11:29.350
okay? And I'm going to add them, but I'm&nbsp;
going to do it in a non-binary fashion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:36.310
okay? I want to add them all together. Let's&nbsp;
see if we can do this, okay—three things in no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:45.280
particular order. Whoops, I just dropped one;&nbsp;
better pick that one up. Okay, there we are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:51.670
back on track here. Okay, we have three multisets.&nbsp;
I'm now going to add—ready? Watch carefully,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:51.670 --> 00:12:04.240
okay? There's no more left in our containers—we&nbsp;
have dumped everything out, and you can see,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:14.410
perhaps, that we have all the coins there in this&nbsp;
new multiset. We have added the three multisets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:14.410 --> 00:12:22.240
together, but we have not done so in a binary way,&nbsp;
right? We've just dumped them all out—independent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:32.230
of order, independent of having to do two at once,&nbsp;
right? In principle, we can have, you know, lots&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.230 --> 00:12:35.530
of different containers, and we're just dumping&nbsp;
them all here. We can have, say, three people&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:35.530 --> 00:12:40.870
doing this—a lot easier. We all sort of dumped&nbsp;
our individual containers into the M-set, we'd be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.870 --> 00:12:51.040
adding the contents. It's a very interesting,&nbsp;
non-standard view of what addition is.

00:12:51.040 --> 00:13:04.030
So, for example, when we're writing stuff down,&nbsp;
okay, here's an M-set of marks, here's an M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.030 --> 00:13:08.980
of marks, here's an M-set of marks. So we&nbsp;
have three natural numbers in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:15.250
and we're going to add these natural numbers&nbsp;
together. What do we do? We create a new M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:23.070
which is obtained by copying each one of these&nbsp;
entries into the M-set here. And how we actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:27.900
do that, well, it's not prescribed. We can do&nbsp;
that in a number of different ways—this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:31.620
here is essentially unordered. We're writing&nbsp;
it in a kind of an ordered way, but that's not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:37.950
really essential. So we could take these ones and&nbsp;
sort of go 1, 1, 1, or maybe I should take mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:44.760
mark, mark, and then mark, and then mark, mark,&nbsp;
mark, mark. We're just dumping out the contents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:52.200
of these three into a new box, conceptually.&nbsp;
I want you to think about having boxes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:56.970
having a number of people just dumping into the&nbsp;
containers, and everything dropping into a box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.970 --> 00:14:04.230
So this is the arithmetical analog of dumping&nbsp;
the contents of several boxes into a new box.

00:14:04.230 --> 00:14:11.370
Now, with this naive, almost physical&nbsp;
understanding of how we add multisets—in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:20.070
case, add numbers, natural numbers—we note that&nbsp;
the commutativity and associativity properties of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.070 --> 00:14:26.070
addition are essentially obvious here, because&nbsp;
we're only dealing with something, a situation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:31.380
where order is unimportant, and the only objects&nbsp;
that we have—in fact, not a variety of coins—we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.380 --> 00:14:36.630
just had these unit marks. That's all that ever&nbsp;
appears in our natural numbers—they're always&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:36.630 --> 00:14:43.770
the same. And the commutativity and associativity&nbsp;
are really obvious notes. If you've got a bunch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.770 --> 00:14:52.080
of primary school students and you've got them&nbsp;
practicing dumping multisets of coins—like, just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:57.810
coins of one type, let's say, you know, ten-cent&nbsp;
pieces—so you have a multiset of ten-cent pieces,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:02.880
each of the kids has a multiset of ten-cent&nbsp;
pieces, and you're, you know, adding all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:07.950
M-sets together, they'd have a lot of fun.&nbsp;
They would quickly determine that, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:15.090
if Jane and Bill combined theirs into a box and&nbsp;
Jane does hers a little bit before Bill and they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.090 --> 00:15:19.140
look at what they get, and then they do it again&nbsp;
and Bill drops his in a little bit before Jane,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:24.810
it's not going to make any difference—the&nbsp;
order is not important. If we have three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.810 --> 00:15:28.020
people and they kind of dump, and one&nbsp;
person gets to dump theirs in first,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:33.450
it's not going to make any difference to&nbsp;
the collection. I'm sure students are going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.450 --> 00:15:38.340
to be able to understand that—it's going to be&nbsp;
obvious to them after a while of playing around.

00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:50.790
So, you know, in particular, and with our linear&nbsp;
way of writing things, if we have this M-set—mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:50.790 --> 00:15:56.520
mark—and this M-set—mark, mark, mark—then we&nbsp;
combine them, we get mark, mark, mark, mark, mark.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:56.520 --> 00:16:01.556
And that's, of course, the same thing as if we&nbsp;
combine mark, mark, mark with mark, mark, mark in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:01.556 --> 00:16:08.970
the usual kind of fashion. Or if we have three of&nbsp;
them, and we combine these guys first, and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:14.340
add that one, well, that's going to be the same as&nbsp;
if we add the first one to the sum of these ones.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:24.090
So even children can be taught this system,&nbsp;
and they can be taught this before they have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.090 --> 00:16:30.000
a language—before they actually have been given&nbsp;
names for the numbers. They don't need to know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:34.860
that this is the number five, this is the number&nbsp;
three, this is the number two—we can just refer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:40.590
to this as the M-set "mark, mark, mark," and this&nbsp;
is the M-set "mark, mark." Maybe we could use the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:46.080
word "units"; maybe it's a little bit better&nbsp;
word—"unit, unit, unit." This one is "unit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:52.020
unit." Okay, so they could deal with things&nbsp;
at that level, and they could get a sense of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:57.360
how this number system works, independent of&nbsp;
having actually a naming system for numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:02.640
So this is a claim that I'm making—it's sort of my&nbsp;
intuition. I haven't actually gone out and taught&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:08.100
kindergarten kids this system, but maybe somebody&nbsp;
could have a go at playing around in this fashion.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:13.410
And maybe somebody has already done this—maybe&nbsp;
it's a standard kind of educational procedure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.410 --> 00:17:20.280
for very young people. In any case, there's&nbsp;
something very simple-minded and, I think,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:28.950
down-to-earth about this very concrete, simple&nbsp;
conceptual framework or approach to arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:37.770
So, especially advantageous is that these basic&nbsp;
properties become essentially obvious facts to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.770 --> 00:17:41.610
even children who are working with such&nbsp;
a system—that's my direct recommendation.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:46.290
All right, so now let's look at&nbsp;
multiplication. How are we going to define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:52.080
multiplication of natural numbers? If we&nbsp;
look at the earlier videos in the series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:55.260
you'll see that we've defined&nbsp;
multiplication there in a somewhat&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.260 --> 00:18:00.270
geometrical fashion. Here we are going to&nbsp;
stick with a more arithmetical approach.

00:18:00.270 --> 00:18:09.000
So, to multiply natural numbers, we're going&nbsp;
to extend this following multiplication of our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:16.860
unit marks. So mark times mark equals mark,&nbsp;
or if we prefer, unit times unit equals unit.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.860 --> 00:18:25.140
We're going to extend that to multiplication of&nbsp;
M-sets of units. So here is an M-set of units,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:29.100
or a natural number, here's another&nbsp;
M-set of units. To form the product,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.100 --> 00:18:35.190
we're just going to take all possible products&nbsp;
between the units here and the units there—note&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:42.240
that one times that, that one times that, and so&nbsp;
on—all possible products, and write each one of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:42.240 --> 00:18:48.840
those possible products down in its own M-set, so&nbsp;
multiplicities are fine. And then we'll replace&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:55.050
each one of these with what they're equal to,&nbsp;
so we just get a unit repeated, in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.050 --> 00:19:01.980
six times. So unit, unit times unit, unit,&nbsp;
unit equals unit, unit, unit, unit, unit, unit.

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:11.280
So multiplying M-sets involves multiplying all&nbsp;
possible products of their elements. It's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:16.380
same procedure, the same orientation that&nbsp;
we had when we were multiplying axles. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:20.730
we might think about this as having a&nbsp;
dramatically simplified multiplication&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:26.970
table—that our new multiplication table for&nbsp;
natural numbers basically just involves this:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.970 --> 00:19:31.350
there's really only one thing to remember,&nbsp;
that a unit times unit equals unit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:37.710
or mark times mark equals mark, or if we prefer,&nbsp;
something times something equals something.

00:19:37.710 --> 00:19:47.730
Now, the distributive law is, I think, almost&nbsp;
obvious now, right? Suppose we have what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:55.140
call 2 times 4 equals 8, and we have what&nbsp;
we could call 3 times 4 equals 12. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:55.140 --> 00:20:01.350
written out with lots of units or marks&nbsp;
instead of the words that we have—well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:06.450
if we've gone through all possible&nbsp;
products between these M-sets to get this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.450 --> 00:20:11.970
and we've gone through all possible products of&nbsp;
these ones to get this, then if we combine these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.970 --> 00:20:19.320
two—if we add these two M-sets to get this one—and&nbsp;
multiply it by the same common M-set over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:25.950
right? Then all the possible products that we're&nbsp;
going to get from now multiplying these marks with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.950 --> 00:20:32.400
these ones—all those possible products are going&nbsp;
to be either of this kind or of this kind. If we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:37.620
think of this thing here as being composed—say,&nbsp;
those first two are from there and the next ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:45.030
are from there—so I think it's pretty clear. If&nbsp;
you got a child to do this enough times, they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.030 --> 00:20:49.620
would catch on that if you are multiplying this&nbsp;
times this, and you know what that is, you know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:49.620 --> 00:20:55.260
what this is, that you could compute the product&nbsp;
here just by taking these two and adding them.

00:20:55.260 --> 00:21:03.930
Of course, the way things would look would&nbsp;
look a lot more extensive than, you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.930 --> 00:21:08.070
much more primitive than what we usually&nbsp;
do with our Hindu-Arabic system, but still,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.070 --> 00:21:13.860
there's something kind of fundamental and&nbsp;
straightforward in principle about this story,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:19.200
even though in practice it gets to be a little&nbsp;
bit onerous for us to write, especially if the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:19.200 --> 00:21:24.090
numbers are big. But the observant viewer will&nbsp;
notice that we haven't quite covered all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.090 --> 00:21:29.610
bases with this multiplication rule that we've&nbsp;
given, because what happens when we multiply,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:36.240
say, the empty M-set with a natural number? This&nbsp;
is also a natural number—it's what we're calling&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:42.300
zero. So what happens if we take 0 times,&nbsp;
say, this M-set? Okay, so the rule is, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:48.870
we're supposed to consider all possible products&nbsp;
of the form unit times unit, where one of them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.870 --> 00:21:56.100
is obtained or taken from the first M-set and the&nbsp;
other one's obtained from the second M-set. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.100 --> 00:22:04.470
but in this case, there are no units in this first&nbsp;
thing, so there are no such products. We cannot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:12.390
form any products—unit times unit—where they're&nbsp;
respectively from both of the ingredient M-sets.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:12.390 --> 00:22:20.790
We cannot, and so the product of these two&nbsp;
natural numbers will also be necessarily empty.

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:32.850
Another thing to observe is that associativity&nbsp;
of multiplication, which is a more subtle issue,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:32.850 --> 00:22:44.520
right? Why is 3 times 4 times 5 the same as&nbsp;
3 times 4 times 5? That essentially really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:52.650
ultimately boils down to this associative law—the&nbsp;
fact that unit times unit times unit is the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:52.650 --> 00:22:59.280
as unit times unit times unit. That's true because&nbsp;
this thing here is a unit, so this is just unit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:03.180
times unit, so this left-hand side, it's just&nbsp;
about becoming a unit. And it's also true of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:08.070
the right-hand side—that's a unit, and one times&nbsp;
or unit times unit is unit, so we're getting unit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:14.880
on both sides, so they're equal, right? So this&nbsp;
fundamental associativity at the level of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:23.130
units themselves then goes up to associativity&nbsp;
of multiplication of natural numbers.

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:29.820
So if we wanted to multiply, say, what we&nbsp;
would call 2 times 4 times 3 in this order,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:36.510
we get the same as 2 times 4 times 3, because all&nbsp;
of the various products, say, that are involved on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:36.510 --> 00:23:43.080
the left-hand side look like what? So the entries&nbsp;
of this thing here are things of the form a unit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:48.300
here times a unit here, okay? And then when we&nbsp;
multiply by this M-set, we're taking a unit here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.300 --> 00:23:55.500
times a unit here, multiplying that combination&nbsp;
with one of the units over here. But on this side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.500 --> 00:24:01.650
what we're doing correspondingly is those same&nbsp;
units that we flagged—maybe we color them red or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:08.310
something temporarily—over here, we would see them&nbsp;
again, but then they would correspond to a product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:12.120
over here. So here, the red one times the red one&nbsp;
would appear on the right-hand side, and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:18.450
multiply by the red one here. So basically, we're&nbsp;
using the same law here, just applying it to all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:24.290
these possible triples of units obtained—unit&nbsp;
here times unit here times unit here.

00:24:24.290 --> 00:24:30.680
So we've seen this kind of argument before in the&nbsp;
maxwell kind of situation. We've observed that if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.680 --> 00:24:38.330
we have an associative product at the pixel level,&nbsp;
that that then lifts to an associative product at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.330 --> 00:24:45.980
the maxwell level once we just define maximum&nbsp;
multiplication as the M-set extension of pixel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.980 --> 00:24:52.280
multiplication. It's exactly the same kind&nbsp;
of story, same kind of pattern. So really,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:58.250
it's the single associativity at the level of&nbsp;
these units which is really responsible for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.250 --> 00:25:06.830
associativity of natural number multiplication. So&nbsp;
there's an argument to be made here, and you know,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:06.830 --> 00:25:12.440
you could convince some primary school student, I&nbsp;
think, by going through this carefully with some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:12.440 --> 00:25:21.080
examples. But it would be just orders of magnitude&nbsp;
more complicated to try to convince someone of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:27.620
the associativity of multiplication using the&nbsp;
20th-century set-theoretical formulation. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.620 --> 00:25:31.700
that's just orders of magnitude much&nbsp;
more complicated and convoluted,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:31.700 --> 00:25:38.510
right? So we are really cutting to the chase&nbsp;
here—I mean, I think we're really boiling things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:43.550
down to pretty well the simplest thing that they&nbsp;
possibly could be with this M-set point of view.

00:25:43.550 --> 00:25:49.190
I think it's valuable to say a little bit more&nbsp;
about the role of nothing in this story so far.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:49.190 --> 00:25:57.770
So we've used nothing to create this empty&nbsp;
M-set, which is then going to play the role&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.770 --> 00:26:04.130
of zero—that's sort of in the traditional way,&nbsp;
very much like in the standard formulation of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.130 --> 00:26:08.720
things. But in addition, I think it's important&nbsp;
to recognize that there's now also a new role&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:17.690
for nothing, which is not just contained in&nbsp;
the empty set. So our basic multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:27.200
for example, right? We stated it in terms of just&nbsp;
being between unit and unit—unit times unit equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:27.200 --> 00:26:33.960
unit. But we saw that actually it's a little&nbsp;
bit more expansive, a little bit more precise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:42.360
to also say what happens to the nothing times&nbsp;
unit. So there's really these two aspects of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:42.360 --> 00:26:47.430
things: there's nothing and there's something.&nbsp;
And what we've already observed or defined is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:47.430 --> 00:26:54.690
something times something equals something. The&nbsp;
story is really completed by this more elaborate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:54.690 --> 00:26:59.820
multiplication table, which includes also the&nbsp;
fact that nothing times nothing equals nothing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:59.820 --> 00:27:04.530
So you can see that there's nothing and there's&nbsp;
nothing, and nothing times nothing equals nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:10.410
all right? And also that nothing times something,&nbsp;
represented by that entry there, is the same as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:10.410 --> 00:27:14.970
something times nothing, represented by&nbsp;
that entry there, which is nothing, okay?

00:27:14.970 --> 00:27:21.690
So the true multiplication table, sorted at&nbsp;
the level below the natural numbers themselves,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:21.690 --> 00:27:31.230
arguably has these two objects or two&nbsp;
concepts involved. There's both the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.230 --> 00:27:36.510
nothing and the something—it's just that the&nbsp;
nothing we're agreeing, we're going to write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:36.510 --> 00:27:44.310
it as an empty page or as an empty piece of our&nbsp;
page, and so it ends up looking blank. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:49.410
but it's a new kind of way of thinking&nbsp;
about nothing and the role of nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:54.630
that we're going to actually have something&nbsp;
blank. It's not going to be a symbol that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:54.630 --> 00:28:00.120
represents that blankness—the actual blankness&nbsp;
itself is going to be addressed; we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:00.120 --> 00:28:05.820
acknowledge it to let it be what it wants to be.&nbsp;
It's just empty, and so we look and we see, "Oh,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:10.800
there's emptiness there." It's not as if somebody&nbsp;
has forgotten to write something, right? It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:17.820
meant to be empty—it is empty. It's a new kind of&nbsp;
thinking that's going to be very valuable for us.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:17.820 --> 00:28:23.220
It's very oriented towards an M-set point of view.&nbsp;
When we're doing arithmetic with M-sets, and we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:28.560
going to jack this up to doing algebra involving&nbsp;
M-sets as well, linear algebra, and so on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:28.560 --> 00:28:35.850
we're going to see more and more the usefulness of&nbsp;
being able to think about nothing as just being an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:35.850 --> 00:28:42.270
empty part of the page, not being represented&nbsp;
by a symbol—just letting it be nothing.

00:28:45.420 --> 00:28:51.630
Okay, so we have the beginnings now of a new&nbsp;
kind of arithmetic, right? An arithmetic which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:57.300
is multiset-oriented, which incorporates these&nbsp;
fundamental aspects of nothing and something,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:57.300 --> 00:29:06.120
and which really ends up being aligned very much&nbsp;
with a naive layperson's approach to what natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:12.510
numbers might be, at the most simplistic kind&nbsp;
of level. So I think there's going to be a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:18.300
of theoretical implications of this, but there's&nbsp;
also educational aspects that I think are worth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:25.620
touching upon. In particular, there is the&nbsp;
connection between these numbers that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:33.180
invoking here and the names for the numbers. So we&nbsp;
need to have a discussion about the importance of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:42.360
naming numbers, which also touches base with the&nbsp;
issue of ordering numbers. So those two issues are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:49.920
closely related—ordering and naming—and they're&nbsp;
both things that impact very directly on young&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:58.350
people's original understanding of arithmetic,&nbsp;
how they think about what arithmetic with natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:58.350 --> 00:30:04.530
numbers is. So I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger—thanks for listening.

